Just had an unforgettable convo with Ernesto..my favorite @uber driver ever!! When he was 19 years old, Ernesto & 3 friends jumped on a raft in Cuba and somehow survived 4 days & nights thru scorching sun, freezing cold nights, and too many close calls with sharks to count.  After a cruise ship was unable to stop and rescue them, the @uscg was called, and the rest is history.  Ernesto became a  US citizen, and worked for 10 years to legally bring his mother and sister to the US.  He recently became a grandfather, and says he owes everything to America and the great state of Florida.  I'll never forget his story, or his words: "How can you appreciate the bed you sleep in every night if you've never slept on the floor?" 
Thank you, Ernesto, for being so kind, and for loving and appreciating our imperfect yet wonderful country. 🇺🇸🙏🏽

Every time I come to this Whole Foods, I see this man and his beautiful smiling face.  So today, I decided to introduce myself, and wow!  I am SOOO glad I did because Edmund is incredible!! 

I just wanted him to know that his smile & friendly attitude make ME smile, and I've noticed that he has the same effect on so many people...many of whom usually don't even make eye contact in these aisles! 

He said he's always been that way - even as a little kid who grew up in Barbados and came to NYC as a teenager.  He said that recently, a man he had never met came up to him in the aisle and thanked him...saying that Edmund's kind words, constant smile and positive energy helped him heal from cancer!!! 
(So then I started crying...not surprising at all to those of you who know me 😂) 

In Edmund's words, it's proof that you never know what someone is going through, so ALWAYS smile & try to be a light in someone's life...even if it's only for a moment! 

Edmund, THANK YOU for being you!! 

And to the management at this @wholefoods in Avon, CT... please celebrate Edmund!  He is a gem! ❤️

So happy for @orlandomagic  forward Jonathan Isaac, who has created an incredible clothing line called @weareunitus that represents the values I believe in for myself and my family 🤍 

I just wore them for a 10 hour international flight & I've never been more comfortable! 

This is not an ad, I'm not getting paid, I just want to help spread the word about a really impressive, brave young man who is doing good for others, and shining brightly despite the hatred and negativity that comes his way just for speaking his truth.
(If you don't remember how he was treated in the @nba bubble during COVID, look it up.  It was disgusting.  But the book he wrote afterwards explains how & why he's able to stand tall)

This quote about his new line is EVERYTHING!! 

@jonisaac_01 : 
"UNITUS is a sports and apparel company and the basis of it for me is freedom," Isaac said. "You have companies in that field who have made a conscious decision to either attack or undermine Christian values, conservative values...things like that. And I think they have the free choice to do so, as much as I disagree, but I feel that we also have a freedom to create what we want to create."

So proud to know you, Jonathan! 
Keep being you!! 
🙏🏽🇺🇸🤍

#weareunitus 
#truegreatness
#jonathanisaac
🤍 #steelestrong

✨ Meet Danielle ✨ Connecting flights today through Atlanta, I stopped at the restroom and was greeted by her beautiful smile & the most incredible attitude... welcoming the long line of women into "her bathroom", striking up conversations, and wishing all of us a "blessed day" on our way out. 

When I stopped to thank her for her kindness, we began chatting and she said, "the B9 bathroom has been MINE for a total of 7 years...and its always the cleanest bathroom in this entire airport!" She went on to say that other supervisors have tried to steal her to come to take care of their bathrooms, but she won't leave B9. 

The pride she exudes for her bathroom was awesome to see.... unforgettable, actually.  And her kindness caused every single woman & girl in there to smile, which she says makes HER day! 

So I asked where her positivity comes from, and she said her late mother... who succumbed to ovarian cancer in 2014.  Danielle says she just tries to honor her mother, who ALWAYS led with kindness ❤️ 

So ladies, if you're ever in the @Delta terminal at @atlairport (Mondays through Saturdays...she only has Sundays off!) stop by the restroom at gate B9 and say hello to Danielle.  It will absolutely make your day, and hers! ❤️ 

#kindness
#leadingwithkindness

Episode 011 | Sage Steele: Standing for Truth⁠
⁠
On today’s show, Bear and Tony speak with sports broadcaster Sage Steele.⁠
⁠
Sage is well-known for hosting numerous shows and live events including SportsCenter’s coverage of the Super Bowl, the NBA Finals, the World Series, The Masters, and many others. She has been a guest on Jimmy Kimmel Live, a featured guest host on The View, and has been featured in publications including Variety, The Wall Street Journal, Huffington Post, and Rolling Stone. ⁠
⁠
The former ESPN anchor recently settled a lawsuit with the network and its parent company Disney. She left the network in 2022, alleging that they infringed upon her free speech and retaliated against her for privately held opinions after, explaining that she had been “sidelined” for speaking out against ESPN’s COVID vaccination policy. ⁠

Tune in on Spotify, YouTube, or Apple Podcast to catch the full episode. Subscribe to the Born Primitive Podcast on your preferred channel to be notified weekly of new episodes.

February 2020.  Backstage at my favorite IU bar @thebluebirdbar ..the night before his long-awaited return to IU 🤍❤️ Bob Knight is the reason why I went to school at Indiana.  He is the reason why I fell in love with the game of basketball.  He was bigger than life, but was always kind & welcoming to me as a shy student/intern, and then later as a young reporter.  Although imperfect, he was so caring & incredibly generous--something most media simply refused to discuss. My absolute fondest memories from my 5 years at IU are gamedays at Assembly Hall.  He influenced so many-including my dad who was an Army cadet during Coach's tenure at West Point.  While he will likely never be fully appreciated for his impact on the game AND literally thousands of young men, he will be forever loved by those of us who took the time to learn who he was as  a man. 
RIP, Coach! THANK YOU!! ❤️🤍❤️

📷 cred: Todd Leary :) 
.
#bobknight

✨Meet Jaime! ✨ He is AWESOME...and inspired me today during our @uber drive to the airport in Fort Lauderdale.  He's 27, works 7 days a week trying to save every penny to bring his wife & 2 year old son to the USA from Ecuador. We talked about so much, including how proud he is to be doing this LEGALLY, while millions of others are allowed to enter illegally, which affects his bottom line (illegals can come and get work visas, which has crowded the driver pool in south Florida) But he is SO optimistic, and says that as hard as it is to be away from his family, if he stayed in Ecuador, he'd only be able to earn $300 PER MONTH!  So, he keeps driving for Uber with a smile on his face, so he can send $$ back to his family, counting the days till he can bring them to America. 
1 1/2 more years! 
Grateful Jaime shared his story :) 🙏🏽🇺🇸

Never thought I'd ever post photos like this but here goes :) They were taken this summer at a friend's beautiful ranch in Bastrop, TX during 4th of July week.  About 60 people were part of the festivities & the only person I knew was the host.  I'm usually okay flying solo, I've gotten pretty good at it, but this was different.  As outgoing as I can be, "Shy Sage" from my younger years sometimes returns & in this case, it almost kept me from saying yes to something that ended up being so special.  Aside from meeting some of the most incredible people, it was a reminder to keep pushing, to keep getting comfortable being uncomfortable. 
.
So I was finishing up a workout in the 95 degree heat when my new friend @georgiaphotonyc asked if I wanted to do an impromptu photo shoot.  I tried to run the other way bc I'm always so awkward in front of cameras, but she's pretty convincing & the rest is history :)
Not only did it end up being fun..it was actually liberating to be that vulnerable..and it was emotional.  SO very emotional. It forced me to be STILL (rare!) and in doing so, allowed me to think deeply about life.  I knew that my beloved career-28 years in broadcasting-was about to drastically change. But it was a long time coming, and I realized how proud I was of myself for standing up for what's right.  But most of all, I thought about how damn grateful I am for my life: my 3 kids, my immediate & extended family, my close friends, and even the thousands of strangers who have been so kind & supportive of me from afar.  I thought about how grateful I am to GOD for giving me the STRENGTH to let go of caring what others think, the STRENGTH to stand up for myself no matter what/how big the foe, and yes, the STRENGTH to keep getting comfortable being uncomfortable-something I've basically mastered over the last 5 years or so :) 
.
It's been awhile since I've looked forward to a new year this much, but I honestly wouldn't change a thing about 2023.  So much growth, so many priceless lessons!  And because of those lessons, I have never felt stronger physically & spiritually. I pray all of you have a happy, healthy & peaceful 2024! 🙏🏽 
Ps-THANK YOU, Georgia❤️
